Text.val: Call a program that can be run in parallel to keep adding entries to the queue.
RqReqLst() returns the total number of requests
RqReqInf() returns information about each request.

Text.valUnicode: {\rtf1\fbidis\ansi\ansicpg1252\deff0\deflang1033{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Microsoft Sans Serif;}{\f1\fswiss\fprq2\fcharset0 Microsoft Sans Serif;}} {\colortbl ;\red0\green0\blue0;\red255\green0\blue128;} {\*\generator Msftedit 5.41.21.2509;}\viewkind4\uc1\pard\ltrpar\cf1\b\f0\fs20 To use this example:\par \par 1. Press\i\f1 Add Test Entries\i0\f0 . This brings up a parallel program that will add entries into the queue. To prevent those entries from being processed, you simply not start the process that would handle them.\par \par 2. Press Refresh. This will use \cf2 RqReqInf()\cf1 to read the queue into a memory table, which will be displayed onscreen.\par \par 3. From the subform list, you can us the buttons to work with one request: \par \par -- \i\f1 Status\i0\f0 : uses\cf2 RqStat()\cf1 : to give the current status of a request\par \par -- \i\f1 Delete Selected\i0\f0 : Uses \cf2 RqReqDel()\cf1 to delete all the entries that are checked. Note that this only changes the status of the request: it remains in the list.\par \par -- \i\f1 Change Priority\i0\f0 : This uses the \cf2 RqReqPri()\cf1 function to change the priority of any checked requests. Again, this only functions if the request has not yet processed.\par }

Text.val: The RqQuePri() function allows you to change the priority of a request that is in the queue.
